Now I understand the issue. Looking at the `fixFunctionBodyExpression` function (starting at line 520), when the body expression starts with an annotation (like `@Suppress("DEPRECATION")`), the function-signature rule still tries to merge the first line of the body expression with the function signature.

The key part is around lines 542-562:
```kotlin
if (whiteSpaceBeforeFunctionBodyExpression.isWhiteSpaceWithNewline()) {
    val mergeWithFunctionSignature =
        if (firstLineOfBodyExpression.length < maxLengthRemainingForFirstLineOfBodyExpression) {
            functionBodyExpressionWrapping == default ||
                (functionBodyExpressionWrapping == multiline && functionBodyExpressionLines.size == 1) ||
                node.isMultilineFunctionSignatureWithoutExplicitReturnType(
                    lastNodeOfFunctionSignatureWithBodyExpression,
                )
        } else {
            false
        }
    if (mergeWithFunctionSignature) {
        emit(
            whiteSpaceBeforeFunctionBodyExpression!!.startOffset,
            "First line of body expression fits on same line as function signature",
            true,
        )
        if (autoCorrect) {
            (whiteSpaceBeforeFunctionBodyExpression as LeafPsiElement).rawReplaceWithText(" ")
        }
    }
}
```

The issue is that when the body expression starts with an annotation (annotated expression), it should NOT be merged with the function signature because doing so violates the `annotation` rule which requires a newline before the annotation.

I need to check if the body expression starts with an annotation and if so, not merge it. Let me look for an `ANNOTATED_EXPRESSION` element type.

